'''John Wesley Hardin''' (May 26, 1853 – August 19, 1895) was an [[United States|American]] [[American Old West|Old West]] [[outlaw]], [[gunslinger|gunfighter]], and controversial [[folk hero|folk icon]]. The son of a Methodist preacher, Hardin got into trouble with the law from an early age. He killed his first man at age 14, he claimed in self-defense.

Pursued by lawmen for most of his life, he was sentenced in 1877 at age 25 to 25 years in prison for murder. When he was sentenced, Hardin claimed to have killed 42 men<ref name="Marohn-gun"/> but contemporary newspapers accounts attributed only 27 deaths to him.<ref name="twentyseven"/> While in prison, Hardin studied law and wrote an autobiography. He was well known for wildly exaggerating or completely making up stories about his life. He claimed credit for many murders that cannot be corroborated.<ref name="Hardin Autobiography"/>{{rp|10–11}}

Within a year of his release in 1894, Hardin was killed by [[John Selman]] in an [[El Paso, Texas|El Paso]] saloon.

== Early life ==

Hardin was born in 1853 near [[Bonham, Texas|Bonham]], [[Texas]], to a [[Methodist]] preacher and [[Circuit rider (religious)|circuit rider]], James "Gip" Hardin, and Mary Elizabeth Dixson.<ref name="1860 U S Census"/><ref name="lawmen">{{cite book |title = The Encyclopedia of Lawmen, Outlaws, and Gunfighters |last = Metz |first = Leon Claire |coauthors =  |year = 2003 |publisher = Checkmark Books |isbn = 0-8160-4543-7 |pages = }}</ref>{{rp|108–100}} He was named after [[John Wesley]], the founder of the [[Methodism|Methodist]] denomination of the Christian church.<ref name="GF">{{cite book | last =Trachtman | first =Paul| authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Old West: The Gunfighters | publisher = Time Life| year = 1974| location = New York| page = 238| isbn = 978-0-8094-1481-9}}; during the description of one book in the series, ''The Gunfighters'', the well-known claim is made: "John Wesley Hardin, so mean, he once shot a man just for snoring too loud."</ref>{{rp|238}} In his autobiography, Hardin described his mother as "blond, highly cultured ... [while] charity predominated in her disposition."<ref name="Hardin Autobiography">{{cite book | first = John Wesley | last = Hardin | title = The Life of John Wesley Hardin: As Written By Himself | isbn = 978-0-8061-1051-6 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=jLM-AAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=john+wesley+hardin#v=onepage&q&f=false | publisher = Smith & Moore |location=Seguin, Texas | year = 1896 | accessdate = March 30, 2011}}</ref>{{rp|5}} Hardin's father traveled over much of central Texas on his preaching circuit until he settled his family in Sumpter, [[Trinity County, Texas|Trinity County]], Texas in 1859. There, Joseph Hardin established and taught at the school that John Hardin and his siblings attended. Hardin was the second surviving son of ten children.<ref name="Metz">{{cite book | title = John Wesley Hardin: Dark Angel of Texas | last = Metz | first = Leon Claire | coauthors = | date = Sep 1996 | publisher = (First Edition), Mangan Books, El Paso, Texas | ISBN= 0-930208-35-8 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=jSKQB4ayKaIC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false | accessdate = April 25, 2013}}</ref>{{rp|1}}

In 1862, at age nine, Hardin tried to run away and join the [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] army.<ref name="Hardin Autobiography"/>{{rp|10–11}}

=== Trouble at school ===

In 1867,<ref name="Hardin Autobiography"/>{{rp|7}} while attending his father's school, Hardin was taunted by another student, Charles Sloter. Sloter accused Hardin of being the author of graffiti on the schoolhouse wall that insulted a girl in his class. Hardin denied writing the poetry, claiming in turn that Sloter was the author.<ref name="Metz"/> Sloter charged at Hardin with a knife but Hardin stabbed him with his own knife, almost killing him.<ref name="lawmen"/><ref name="gunfighters">{{cite book | title = Encyclopedia of Western Gunfighters |last = O'Neal |first = Bill |coauthors = |year = 1979 |publisher = University of Oklahoma Press |isbn = 0-8061-1508-4 |pages = 126–131}}</ref> Hardin was nearly expelled over the incident.<ref name="Metz"/>

=== First killing ===

In November 1868, when he was 15, Hardin challenged his uncle Holshousen's former slave, Major "Maje" Holshousen, to a wrestling match, which Hardin won.<ref name="Marohn-gun">{{cite book | first = Richard C. | last = Marohn | title = The Last Gunfighter: John Wesley Hardin |edition=Third printing| isbn = 978-0-932702-99-9 | url = | work = Creative Publishing Company |location= College Station, TX | year = June 1995}}</ref> According to Hardin, the following day, Maje "ambushed" him as he rode past shouting at him and waving a stick. Hardin drew his revolver and shot Maje five times. Hardin wrote in his autobiography that he rode to get help for the wounded man, but he died three days later.<ref name="Hardin Autobiography"/>{{rp|13}}<ref group=notes>On December 9, 1868, Lt Charles Schmidt, the [[Freeman's Bureau]] agent based in Sumpter, Texas reported Maje's death to the Assistant Adj. General of the [[Freeman's Bureau]] in a report the titled "Criminal offenses":  "John Hardin (white) – Major Holshousen (fr[eeman]), Murder." Quote: "Hardin, a mere lad shot him without cause as the latter did not like the abuse of Hardin. He shot him five times every wound dangerous. No action taken by civil authorities. Hardin left the county. He lived at Sumpter, [[Trinity County, Texas|Trinity Co]], Texas." Additional: In the margin under the date December 9, 1868 is written the following postscript: "Murder was committed in [[Polk County, Texas|Polk Co, Texas]] about ten 10 miles from [[Moscow, Texas|Moscow]]"</ref><ref>[https://familysearch.org/pal:/MM9.3.1/TH-1942-27424-39426-52?cc=1989155&wc=94K7-3TG:266076801,266080201 ''Criminal Offenses'']  familysearch.org; Texas, Freedmen's Bureau ... Office Records, 1865-1870, Sumpter, Roll 26, Letters sent, vol (158), June-Dec 1867, Apr-Dec 1868; p.112 Image 60</ref> Hardin further wrote that his father did not believe he would receive a fair hearing in the [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]]-occupied state (where more than a third of the state police were former slaves), so he ordered him into hiding.<ref name="Marohn-gun"/> Hardin claimed that the authorities eventually discovered his location and three Union soldiers were sent to arrest him, at which time he "chose to confront his pursuers" despite having been warned of their approach by an older brother, Joseph:<ref name="James">{{cite book | first = Garry | last = James | coauthors = | title = Guns of the Gunfighters |isbn= 978-0-8227-0095-1| url = | work = Peterson Textbook Publishing Company | year = 1975}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book | first = Alton| last = Pryor| title=Outlaws and Gunslingers| isbn = 0-9660053-6-8| url = | work = Stagecoach Publishing| year = 2001}}</ref>

{{quote|... I waylaid them, as I had no mercy on men whom I knew only wanted to get my body to torture and kill. It was war to the knife for me, and I brought it on by opening the fight with a [[double-barreled shotgun]] and ended it with a [[Caplock mechanism|cap and ball]] [[six-shooter]]. Thus it was by the fall of 1868 I had killed four men and was myself wounded in the arm.<ref name="Hardin Autobiography"/>{{rp|14}} }}

== Fugitive from justice ==

Hardin knew he could not return home. As a fugitive, he traveled initially with outlaw Frank Polk in the [[Pisgah, Texas|Pisgah]] area of [[Navarro County, Texas]]. Polk had killed a man named Tom Brady, and a detachment of soldiers sent from [[Corsicana, Texas]] pursued the duo. Hardin escaped but the soldiers apprehended Polk and jailed him temporarily.<ref name="Metz1998">{{cite book|author=Leon Claire Metz|title=John Wesley Hardin: Dark Angel of Texas|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jSKQB4ayKaIC&pg=PA18|date=1 March 1998|publisher=University of Oklahoma Press|isbn=978-0-8061-2995-2|page=18}}</ref> Hardin also briefly taught school in Pisgah. While there, he claimed he shot a man's eye out to win a bottle of whiskey in a bet.<ref name="Hardin Autobiography"/>{{rp|16}} Hardin also claimed that he and his cousin, "Simp" Dixon, encountered a group of soldiers and each killed a man.<ref name="Hardin Autobiography"/>{{rp|17}} Allegedly, Hardin killed a black man in [[Leon County, Texas|Leon County]], Texas.<ref name="DMN2"/>
On January 5, 1870, Hardin was playing cards with Benjamin Bradley in [[List of ghost towns in Texas|Towash]], [[Hill County, Texas]]. Hardin was winning almost every hand, which angered Bradley who threatened to "cut out his liver" if he won again. Bradley drew a knife and a [[Revolver|six-shooter]]. Hardin said he was unarmed and excused himself but claims that later that night, Bradley came looking for him. Bradley allegedly fired a shot at Hardin and missed; Hardin drew both his pistols and returned fire, one shot striking Bradley in the head and the other in his chest.<ref name="Hardin Autobiography"/>{{rp|20}} Dozens of people saw this fight, and from them there is a good record of how Hardin had used his guns. His [[holster]]s were sewn into his vest so that the butts of his pistols pointed inward across his chest. He crossed his arms to draw. Hardin claimed this was the fastest way to draw, and he practised every day. A man called "Judge Moore", who held Hardin's stakes of money and a pistol, but refused to give them up without Bradley's consent, later "vanished".<ref name="Hardin Autobiography"/>{{rp|20}}<ref name="DMN2"/><ref name="DMN1">[http://api.ning.com/files/WP9XTdTmM2BwVue7PdQ*ahkCI59Bmp89oNEocLnxdMDjIkb68Wd56xWyZ6i*YPkf2B7t8TlHbP2a58aLZNSW1Lk9y22vBcue/Image19.jpg ''Article'']; Dallas Morning News; Match 6, 1892. p.3</ref> Hardin eventually admitted killing two men in Hill County.<ref>[http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=pv&GRid=11430987&PIpi=46876344 ''Article'' plate]; August 30, 1877 article; Dallas Democratic Statesman; at [[Find a Grave]]; accessed Aug 2016</ref>

After killing Bradley, Hardin claimed that when a posse of fifteen men came after him, he captured two of them and took a [[shotgun]], two six-shooters, a [[rifle]], and two [[derringer]]s from his captives. He then ordered the two men to join the other members of the posse at Jim Page's and wait for him to come along-"... I reckon they are waiting for me yet.."<ref name="Hardin Autobiography"/>{{rp|22}}

Later that month, on January 20, in Horn Hill, [[Limestone County, Texas]], Hardin claimed he killed a man in a gunfight after an argument at the [[circus]].<ref name="Hardin Autobiography"/>{{rp|23}} Less than a week after this incident, in nearby [[Kosse, Texas]], Hardin was accompanying a prostitute home when they were accosted by her pimp, who demanded money. Hardin threw money on the ground and shot the would-be thief when he bent over to pick it up.<ref name="Hardin Autobiography"/>{{rp|24}}<ref name="James"/>

=== Arrest and escape ===

In January 1871, Hardin was arrested for the murder of the [[Waco, Texas]] [[city marshal]], Laban John Hoffman. However, he denied having committed this crime.<ref name="Hardin Autobiography"/>{{rp|30}} Following his arrest, he was held temporarily in a log jail in the town of [[Marshall, Texas|Marshall]], awaiting transfer to Waco for trial. While locked up, he bought a revolver from another prisoner. Two [[Texas State Police|Texas state policemen]], Captain Edward T. Stakes and an officer named Jim Smalley,<ref name="Hardin Autobiography"/>{{rp|30–31}}<ref>Hardin misspells Stakes name as "Stokes" and Smalley name as "Smolly"</ref> were assigned to escort Hardin to Waco for trial. According to Hardin, they tied him on a horse with no saddle for the trip. While making camp along the way, Hardin escaped when Stakes went to procure [[fodder]] for the horses. He claims he was left alone with Smalley, who began to taunt and beat the then-17-year-old prisoner with the butt of a pistol. Hardin says he feigned crying and huddled against his pony's flank. Hidden by the animal, he pulled out a gun, fatally shot Smalley, and used his horse to escape. Hardin then claimed that while on the run he was "arrested" by three men named Smith, Jones, and Davis, but in [[Bell County, Texas]] he killed all three with their own guns after they became drunken and careless and escaped again.<ref name="Hardin Autobiography"/>{{rp|30–32}}

A Texas Historical Marker notes that in the 1870s Hardin hid out in the vicinity of [[Pilgrim, Texas]].<ref>[http://www.tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/hnp33]; Texas Handbook</ref> After the Bell County shootings, Hardin found refuge with his cousins, the Clements, who were then living in [[Gonzales, Texas|Gonzales]] in south Texas. They suggested he could make money by driving cattle to [[Kansas]] as a [[cowboy]]. Thinking he could get out of Texas long enough for his pursuers to lose interest, Hardin worked with his cousins, [[Cattle raiding|rustling]] cattle for Jake Johnson and Columbus Carol.<ref>{{findagrave|46876344}}</ref><ref>[http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=pv&GRid=11430987&PIpi=46876344 ''Article'' plate]; August 30, 1877 article; ''Dallas Democratic Statesman''; at [[Find a Grave]]; January 2017; Note: the Statesman reported that Hardin rustled cattle to sell in Kansas, and that a brother in "Commanche" [sic] helped by preparing false bills of sale.</ref><ref group=notes>State Seals were found on Joseph Hardin after his lynching.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=U_0DAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA352&dq=Joseph+Hardin+had+state+Seals&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Yhj0UZS3O4_K4APr0oHwDg&ved=0CDoQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Joseph%20Hardin%20had%20state%20Seals&f=false ''The Texas Civil Appeals Reports: Cases Argued and Determined...'']; Volume 29; 1903; p. 352; accessed August 2016</ref> Hardin writes that he was made trail boss for the herd. In February 1871, while the herd was being collected for the drive to Kansas, a [[freedman]], Bob King, attempted to cut a [[Beef cattle|beef cow]] out of the herd. When he refused to obey Hardin's demand to stop, Hardin hit him over the head with his pistol. That same month, Hardin may have wounded three Mexicans in an argument over a [[Three-card Monte]] card game, [[pistol-whipping]] one man over the head, shooting one man in the arm, and shooting the third man in the lung.<ref name="Hardin Autobiography"/>{{rp|33–34}}

While driving cattle on the [[Chisholm Trail]] to [[Abilene, Kansas]], in the summer of 1871, Hardin is reputed to have fought Mexican [[vaquero]]s and cattle rustlers.<ref name="James"/> Towards the end of the drive, a Mexican herd crowded in behind Hardin's and there was some trouble keeping the two herds apart. Hardin exchanged words with the man in charge of the other herd; both men were on horseback. The Mexican fired his gun at Hardin, putting a hole through Hardin's hat. Hardin found that his own weapon, a worn-out cap-and-ball pistol with a loose cylinder, would not fire. He dismounted and managed to discharge the gun by steadying the cylinder with one hand and pulling the trigger with the other. He hit the Mexican in the thigh. A truce was declared and both parties went their separate ways. However, Hardin borrowed a pistol from a friend and went looking for the Mexican, this time fatally shooting him through the head. A firefight between the rival camps ensued. Hardin claimed six vaqueros died in the exchanges (five of them reportedly shot by him)<ref name="GF"/><ref name="Hardin Autobiography"/>{{rp|39–42}}<ref group=notes>In Hardin's autobiographical version of the gunfight, he claims the first fatality was the Mexican he had previously wounded, "Hosea", and that he was the boss vaquero. He wrote that he and Jim Clements prevented the rest of the vaqueros – aside from those who were already killed – from firing on them by deliberately stampeding the Mexican herd.</ref> although this claim appears exaggerated—only three Mexican vaqueros were killed.<ref>[http://api.ning.com/files/-5YwiIyenR*kuOR9st6yloPr1sUZhWEEtF2otI6XCX3TdP3S8Q6eit6vqh0r-7sy6BDzCCVBLPIdJfkTJn9nDQJkAo7uMYTN/Image17.jpg ''Article''] from ''The Wichita Tribune'' June 1, 1871, which reports three cattle herders killed at Park City, Shedgwick Co Kansas c/o researcher Tucker of the Wichita Public Library</ref><ref>[http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn84027670/1871-06-08/ed-1/seq-3/;words=Mexican ''Article'']; ''Saline County Journal''; June 8, 1871; p. 3, Col. 2; accessed May 2016. Report which confirms that the week before, three Mexican herders were killed at Park City, Shedgwick County, Kansas.</ref> Hardin also claimed to have killed two Indians in separate gunfights on the same cattle drive. The first instance was when an Indian tried to shoot an arrow at him on the [[South Canadian River]]. Hardin shot him and then had the body buried to avoid retribution from the man's tribe. The second incident, at Bluff Creek, Kansas, occurred when Indians wanted to collect a "tax" on the cattle. Hardin hit an Indian over the head who he claimed had stolen a silver bridle from him. He then forced a war party to flee after he shot a second Indian who had killed a beef cow.<ref name="Hardin Autobiography"/>{{rp|28–37}}

After arriving in [[Abilene, Texas|Abilene]], Hardin claimed that he and a companion named Pain got into an argument in a restaurant with an anti-Texan, which left Pain wounded in one arm and the stranger shot in the mouth by Hardin's bullet. Hardin fled Abilene to the Cottonwood Trail.<ref name="Hardin Autobiography"/>{{rp|46}}

On July 4, 1871, a Texas trail boss named William Cohron,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GSln=Cohron&GSfn=William&GSbyrel=all&GSdyrel=all&GSst=18&GScntry=4&GSob=n&GRid=96038977&df=all&|title=William M Cohron (1848 - 1871) - Find A Grave Memorial|publisher=}}</ref> was killed on the Cottonwood Trail (40 miles south of Abilene) by an unnamed Mexican, who "fled south"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82015486/1871-07-20/ed-1/seq-2/;words%3D |title=Article |date= July 20, 1871 |publisher= Abilene–White Cloud–Kansas Chief |page= 3 }}</ref> and was subsequently killed by two cowboys in a [[Sumner County, Kansas]], restaurant on July 20.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82015486/1871-07-27/ed-1/seq-2/%3Bwords%3D/ |title=Article |date= July 27, 1871 |publisher= Abilene–White–Cloud, Kansas Chief|page= 2 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://api.ning.com/files/ykd**7NrFwYQxBYIsLtebQwhSBRVvhAxbD*jeq882qrfyaRW0uNL*C9VuopE2Bur8U7YKR-LP2JZKg8GARIG0jLXufJFkehx/Image27.jpg  |title=Article |date=August 17, 1871 |publisher=Abilene Daily Chronicle}}.</ref> Hardin admitted to being involved in the shooting of the Mexican.<ref name="Hardin Autobiography"/>{{rp|46–49}}<ref group=notes>In Hardin's version of the killing, he names the murdered cattleman as "Billy Coran" and the Mexican as "Bideno".</ref>

=== Encounters with "Wild Bill" Hickok ===

[[File:Ben-Thompson.gif|thumb|200px|right|Ben Thompson, as Austin City Marshal 1881–1882]]
[[File:Wild-Bill-5.jpg|thumb|200px|right|J.B. "Wild Bill" Hickok]]
The Bull's Head Tavern, in Abilene, Kansas, had been established as a partnership between ex-lawman [[Ben Thompson (lawman)|Ben Thompson]] and gambler [[Phil Coe]]. The two entrepreneurs had painted a picture of a bull with a large erect penis on the side of their establishment as an advertisement. Citizens complained to [[marshal|Town Marshal]] "[["Wild Bill" Hickok|Wild Bill" Hickok.]] When Thompson and Coe refused his request to remove the bull, Hickok altered it himself. Infuriated, Thompson tried to incite his new acquaintance, Hardin, by exclaiming to him: "He's a damn [[Yankee]]. Picks on [[Johnny Reb|Rebels]], especially Texans, to kill." Hardin, then under the assumed name "Wesley Clemmons" (but better known to the townspeople by the alias "Little Arkansaw"), seemed to have had respect for Hickok, and replied, "If Bill needs killing why don't you kill him yourself?"<ref name="Hardin Autobiography"/>{{rp|44}} Later that night, Hardin was confronted by Hickok, who told him that he was wearing guns in violation of town ordinance, and ordered to hand over his guns, which he did, but in a quite surprising way:<ref>[http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=pv&GRid=11430987&PIpi=46876344 ''Dallas Daily Statesman''plate]; August 30, 1877</ref> Hardin reached down, picked his revolvers up from the holsters, and handed the guns to Wild Bill butts forward, then swiftly rolled them over in his hands and suddenly Wild Bill was staring right into the barrels. However, both men did back down.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=K3_CU7eNeNk&t=963 Tales of the Gun: The Gunslingers]. Historian [[Leon Claire Metz|Leon Metz]] on the encounter of John W. Hardin and "Wild Bill" Hickok (16:03).</ref> Hickok had no knowledge that Hardin was a wanted man, and he advised Hardin to avoid problems while in Abilene.

Hardin met up with Hickok again while on a cattle drive in August 1871. This time, Hickok allowed Hardin to carry his pistols into town - something he had never allowed others to do. For his part, Hardin (still using his alias) was fascinated by Wild Bill and reveled in being seen on intimate terms with such a celebrated gunfighter.<ref name="Hardin Autobiography"/>{{rp|50–51}} Hardin alleged that when his cousin, Mannen Clements, was jailed for the killing of two cowhands Joe and Dolph Shadden in July 1871, Hickok &ndash; at Hardin's request &ndash; arranged for his escape.<ref name="Hardin Autobiography"/>{{rp|pp.54–56}}<ref>[http://www.thewittliffcollections.txstate.edu/research/a-z/hardin.html John Wesley Hardin Collection] [[Texas State University–San Marcos|Texas State University]].</ref>

=== Kills snoring man ===

Soon afterwards on August 6, 1871, Hardin, his cousin Gip Clements, and a rancher friend named Charles Couger put up for the night at the American House Hotel after an evening of gambling. Clements and Hardin shared one room, with Couger in the adjacent room. All three had been drinking heavily. Sometime during the evening, Hardin was awakened by loud snoring coming from Couger's room. He first shouted several times for the man to "roll over" and then, irritated by the lack of response, drunkenly fired several bullets through the shared wall in an apparent effort to awaken him. Couger was hit in the head by the second bullet as he lay in bed, and was killed instantly. Although Hardin may not have intended to kill Couger, he had violated an ordinance prohibiting firing a gun within the city limits. Half-dressed and still drunk, he and Clements exited through a second-story window onto the roof of the hotel. He saw Hickok arrive with four policemen. "Now, I believed," Hardin wrote, "that if Wild Bill found me in a defenseless condition he would take no explanation, but would kill me to add to his reputation."<ref name="Hardin Autobiography"/>{{rp|45–58}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://api.ning.com/files/IHhFP4EFbq02p4VTfzON1GB-tFQGBGaksisrzXoeABYfphA-K2nQKOKAmzvOV0oq-bngooNpfu1rfm85O4t0-VVMnOh0MOu0/Image26.jpg |title= Article |date=August 9, 1871 |publisher=Kansas Daily Commonwealth}}</ref><br> A newspaper reported, "A man was killed in his bed at a hotel in Abilene, Monday night, by a desperado called {{'}}Arkansas{{'}}. The murderer escaped. This was his sixth murder."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn84027670/1871-08-10/ed-1/seq-3/ |title= Article |date=August 10, 1871|publisher= Saline County Journal |page= 3}}</ref> Hardin leapt from the roof into the street and hid in a haystack for the rest of the night. He then stole a horse and rode to the cow camp 35 miles outside town. Hardin claimed he ambushed lawman Tom Carson and two other deputies there. According to Hardin, he did not kill them but forced them to remove all their clothing and walk back to Abilene.<ref name="Hardin Autobiography"/>{{rp|60}} Carson denied the incident ever took place. The next day, Hardin left for Texas, never to return to Abilene.

The incident earned Hardin a reputation as a man "so mean, he once shot a man for snoring".<ref>Trachtman, Paul (1974). Old West: The Gunfighters. New York: Time Life. p. 238. {{ISBN|978-0-8094-1481-9}}.; During the description of one book in the series, The Gunfighters, the well-known claim is made.</ref> Years later, Hardin made a casual reference to the episode: "They tell lots of lies about me," he complained. "They say I killed six or seven men for snoring. Well, it ain't true. I only killed one man for snoring."<ref name="GF"/> Later, in his contradictory 1896 autobiography, Hardin completely omitted the "snoring man" from the story, as he related not only a wrong date (July 7 instead of August 6) but claimed the shooting was a case of self-defense, saying that the man he killed had first tried to stab him with a [[dirk]]<ref name="Hardin Autobiography"/>{{rp|58}} and was a burglar who tried to make off with Hardin's pants.<ref>Metz, Leon Claire; ''The Encyclopedia of Lawmen, Outlaws, and Gunfighters''; "Hardin, John Wesley"; p. 109; {{ISBN|0816045437}}</ref>

=== Gunfights 1871–1872 ===

Following his escape, Hardin claimed to be involved in the following gunfights:<ref name="Hardin Autobiography"/>{{rp|63–67}}

* In October 1871, Hardin was involved in a gunfight with two [[Texas Special Police]]men, Private Green Paramore and John Lackey, during which Paramore was killed and Lackey wounded.
* A negro posse from [[Austin, Texas]] came after him for killing Paramore but said that they returned "sadder and wiser" after he ambushed and killed three of them;
* About 45 miles outside [[Corpus Christi, Texas]], after he was followed by two Mexicans, he shot one off his horse while the other "quit the fight".
* On June 19, 1872, Hardin was involved in a gunfight in [[Willis, Texas]];
* On July 26, 1872, Hardin wounded Texas State Policeman Sonny Speights in the arm with a derringer pistol in [[Hemphill, Texas]].

=== Sutton–Taylor feud ===
{{Main|Sutton–Taylor feud}}
In early 1872, Hardin was in south-central Texas, in the area around [[Gonzales County, Texas|Gonzales County]]. It was about this time that Hardin married Jane Bowen and started to keep regular company with her brother, cattle rustler Robert Bowen. While in the area, he also renewed acquaintance with some of his cousins who were allied with a local family, the Taylors (who had been [[feud]]ing with the rival Sutton faction for several years).

On August 7, 1872, Hardin was wounded by a shotgun blast in a gambling dispute at the Gates Saloon in [[Trinity, Texas]]. He was shot by Phil Sublett, who had lost money to him in a poker game. Two buckshot pellets penetrated Hardin's kidney and for a time it looked as if he would die.

While recuperating from his wounds, Hardin decided he wanted to settle down. After surrendering to Sheriff Reagan (brother of [[John Henninger Reagan]]) of [[Cherokee County, Texas]], he was wounded in the right knee by an accidental gunshot from a nervous deputy.<ref name="Hardin Autobiography" />{{rp|73}} Hardin made a sick-bed surrender to authorities, handing over his guns to Sheriff Reagan and asking to be tried for his past crimes in order "to clear the slate". However, when Hardin learned of how many murders Reagan was going to charge him with, he changed his mind. A relative smuggled a [[hacksaw]] to Hardin, who escaped after cutting through the bars of a prison window.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.legendsofamerica.com/we-johnwesleyhardin.html |title=Wesley Hardin & The Shootist Archetype|publisher=Legends of America|accessdate= August 1, 2015}}</ref> In November 1872 Hardin escaped from the Gonzales County, Texas jail despite a guard of six men; a $100 reward was offered for his arrest.

On May 15, 1873, Jim Cox and Jake Christman were killed by the Taylor faction at Tomlinson Creek. Hardin, having by then recovered from the injuries sustained in Sublett's attack, admitted that there were reports that he had led the fights in which these men were killed, but would neither confirm nor deny his involvement: "... but as I have never pleaded to that case, I will at this time have little to say."<ref name="Hardin Autobiography" />{{rp|81}}

Yet Hardin's main notoriety in the Sutton–Taylor feud came from his part in the killing of two lawmen known to be Sutton family allies. In [[Cuero, Texas]], on May 17, 1873, Hardin killed [[DeWitt County, Texas|DeWitt County]] Deputy Sheriff J.B. Morgan, who served under County Sheriff [[Jack Helm]] (a former [[Police captain|captain]] in the Texas State Police and leader of the Sutton force at that time).<ref name="Hardin Autobiography" />{{rp|79}}<ref name="The Texas Vendetta">{{cite book | first = | last = | title = The Texas Vendetta, or, the Sutton–Taylor Feud | isbn = | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=YgBkoOJ5ntIC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Sutton-taylor+feud#v=onepage&q=doughboy&f=false | publisher = J.J. Little & Co. | year = 1880 | accessdate = 2011-03-30}}</ref>{{rp|30}}  Later that day, Hardin killed Helm in the town square of [[Albuquerque, Texas]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/jcs03|title=SUTTON-TAYLOR FEUD|first=SONNICHSEN, C.|last=L.|date=15 June 2010|website=www.tshaonline.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/hva08|title=ALBUQUERQUE, TX|first=DUNN, ROY|last=SYLVAN|date=9 June 2010|website=www.tshaonline.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83021327/1873-07-31/ed-1/seq-1/#date1=07%2F01%2F1873&index=0&rows=20&searchType=advanced&language=&sequence=0&words=Helms+Jack&proxdistance=5&date2=07%2F31%2F1873&ortext=&proxtext=Jack+Helm&phrasetext=&andtext=&dateFilterType=range&page=1|title=Article|date= July 31, 1873|publisher=Weekly Democratic Statesman}}</ref> On the run again in June 1873, Hardin assisted in the escape of his brother-in-law Joshua Bowen from the Gonzales County, Texas jail where he was imprisoned on an 1872 murder charge. Allegedly, Hardin was also involved in this killing of Thomas Holderman.

The Sutton–Taylor feud intensified when Jim and Bill Taylor gunned down Billy Sutton and Gabriel Slaughter<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn84022279/1874-03-21/ed-1/seq-2/#date1=03%2F01%2F1874&index=9&date2=03%2F31%2F1874&searchType=advanced&language=&sequence=0&words=Sutton&proxdistance=5&state=Texas&rows=20&ortext=&proxtext=Sutton&phrasetext=&andtext=&dateFilterType=range&page=1 |title=Article |date= March 21, 1874 |publisher= Dallas Weekly Herald}}</ref> as they waited on a steamboat platform in [[Indianola, Texas]], on March 11, 1874. Tired of the feuding, the two were planning to leave the area for good. Hardin admitted that he and his brother, Joseph, had been involved (along with both Taylors) in the killings.<ref name="Hardin Autobiography" />{{rp|86–87}}

After a brief visit to Florida where he claimed to have been involved in three incidents against Negroes, including a lynching, Hardin met with his wife, Jane, and their young daughter, with whom he had relocated under the assumed name "Swain". Hardin then met up with his "gang" on May 26, 1874, in a [[Comanche, Texas|Comanche]] saloon to celebrate his 21st birthday. Hardin spotted [[Brown County, Texas|Brown County]] Deputy Sheriff Charles Webb entering the premises. He asked Webb if he had come to arrest him. When Webb replied he had not, Hardin invited him into the hotel for a drink. As Webb followed him inside, Hardin claimed he drew his gun. One of Hardin's men yelled out a warning,<ref name="Hardin Autobiography" />{{rp|92}} and in the ensuing gunfight, Webb was shot dead. It was reported at the time that Webb was shot as he was pulling out an arrest warrant for one of Hardin's group.<ref>[http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1900-10-14/ed-1/seq-39/;words=New-York tribune ''Article image'']; October 14, 1900; P. 9; image [#39]; [[New York Tribune]] at the [[Library of Congress]]; from [[Chronicling America]]; accessed August 2015</ref> Two of Hardin's accomplices in the shooting were cousin Bud Dixon and Jim Taylor.<ref name="Hardin Autobiography" />{{rp|92}}

The death of the popular Webb resulted in the quick formation of a [[Lynching|lynch mob]]. Hardin's parents and wife were taken into protective custody, while his brother Joe and two cousins, brothers Bud and Tom Dixon, were arrested on outstanding warrants. A group of local men broke into the jail in July 1874 and hanged Joe, Bud, and Tom.<ref name="Hardin Autobiography" />{{rp|101}}<ref name="WDE1">{{cite web|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn84022109/1874-06-09/ed-1/seq-3/;words=Hardins+Hardin?date1=1868&rows=20&searchType=basic&state=Texas&date2=1880&proxtext=Hardin&y=6&x=7&dateFilterType=yearRange&index=7 |title=Joseph Hardin |date= June 9, 1874 |publisher=The Waco Daily Examiner |page= 3|accessdate= October 1, 2015}}</ref><ref group=notes>It is reported that the hanging ropes were deliberately left too long (in order to cause death through slow strangulation), as grass was found between their toes.</ref> After this, Hardin and Jim Taylor parted ways for good. Hardin would claim that he twice drove away men connected to the feud who had come after him, killing a man in each encounter.<ref name="Hardin Autobiography" />{{rp|105–107}} <ref>Jim Taylor was shot and killed January 1, 1875; Bill Taylor was tried twice and acquitted-he reportedly died about 1890 in Sonora Texas</ref> On November 18, 1875, the leader of the Suttons,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YgBkoOJ5ntIC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Sutton-taylor%20feud#v=snippet&q=Brown&f=false|title=The Texas Vendetta, Or, The Sutton-Taylor Feud|date=1 January 1880|publisher=J.J. Little & Company|via=Google Books}}</ref> ex-Cuero Texas Town Marshal Reuben Brown was shot and killed by five men in Cuero along with a negro named Tom Freeman and another negro was wounded.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83045160/1875-11-19/ed-1/seq-1/#date1=11/01/1875&index=3&rows=20&searchType=advanced&language=&sequence=0&words=Brown%20Reuben&proxdistance=5&date2=02/31/1876&ortext=&proxtext=Reuben%20Brown&phrasetext=&andtext=&dateFilterType=range&page=1|title=Memphis daily appeal. (Memphis, Tenn.) 1847-1886, November 19, 1875, Image 1|date=19 November 1875|publisher=|via=chroniclingamerica.loc.gov}}</ref> In his autobiography Hardin made only two references to Brown: that "Rube" Brown had arrested William Taylor before sending him to [[Galveston, Texas]] for trial,<ref name="Hardin Autobiography" />{{rp|87}} and that Brown had been among the leaders of a Sutton "posse" that had been out to "get"  him in Gonzales County, Texas.<ref name="Hardin Autobiography" />{{rp|106}} It is not known if Hardin was directly or indirectly involved in the killing of Reuben Brown as he makes no further mention of the incident in his life story.

=== Captured and tried ===

[[File:JohnBArmstrong.jpg|thumb|250px|right|John Barclay Armstrong]]

On January 20, 1875, the Texas Legislature authorized Governor [[Richard B. Hubbard]] to offer a $4,000 reward for Hardin's arrest.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=ibc4AAAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=John+Wesley+Hardin+in+Trinity+City+Texas&hl=en&ei=1s2jTJ3_JMG-nAfmwpW-Aw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CDYQ6AEwAzgo#v=onepage&q=hardin&f=false ''Laws passed by the Legislature of Texas 1875'']; p. 189; accessed August 2015.</ref> An undercover [[Texas Ranger Division|Texas Ranger]] named [[John Riley Duncan|Jack Duncan]] intercepted a letter sent to Hardin's father-in-law by his brother-in-law, Joshua Robert "Brown" Bowen. The letter mentioned that Hardin was hiding out on the Alabama-Florida border using the name "James W. Swain". In his autobiography, Hardin admitted that he had "adopted" this alias from [[Brenham, Texas]] Town Marshal Henry Swain who had married a cousin of Hardin's named Molly Parks.<ref name="Hardin Autobiography" />{{rp|109}}

In March 1876 Hardin wounded a man in Florida who had tried to mediate a quarrel between him and another man. In November 1876  Hardin was arrested briefly for having [[marked cards]] in [[Mobile, Alabama]]. Two former slaves of his father's, "Jake" Menzel and Robert Borup, tried to capture Hardin in [[Gainesville, Florida]] in mid-1877. Hardin killed one and blinded the other.<ref name="NewYork">[http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1900-10-14/ed-1/seq-39/;words=Robert+Borup ''Article'']; October 14, 1900 article; New York Tribune; p. 39</ref>

On August 24, 1877,<ref name="twentyseven">{{cite web |url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85032573/1877-08-30/ed-1/seq-2/ |title=Hardin credited with 27 killings |date=August 30, 1877 |publisher= Wichita City Eagle |page= 2 }}</ref><ref group=notes>Whiting, Ala., August 21. To-day as a train was leaving Pensacola, the sheriff, with a posse, boarded the cars to assist Texan officers to arrest the notorious John Wesley Hardin, who is said to have committed twenty-seven murders, and for whose body $1,000 reward has been offered by an act of the Legislature of Texas. His last murder in Texas was the killing of the sheriff of Comanche county.'' ''He has lived in Florida for several years under the name of John Swain. About twenty shots were fired in making the arrest, and Hardin's companion, named Mann, who had a pistol in his hand, was killed.</ref> Rangers and local authorities confronted Hardin on a train in [[Pensacola, Florida]]. He attempted to draw a [[.44 Colt]] cap-and-ball pistol but it got caught up in his [[suspenders]]. The officers knocked Hardin unconscious. They arrested two of his companions and Ranger [[John Barclay Armstrong|John B. Armstrong]] killed a third, a man named Mann, who had a pistol in his hand.<ref>{{cite journal | title=The Trial of John Wesley Hardin |url=http://www.texasbar.com/AM/Template.cfm?Section=Texas_Bar_Journal&Template=/CM/ContentDisplay.cfm&ContentID=17328|last=Wise |first=Ken |date=March 2012 |journal=Texas Bar Journal |volume=75 |series= |issue=9  |page=202 |location=Austin, TX |publisher=State Bar of Texas |editor1-first=Michelle |editor1-last=Hunter |accessdate=March 4, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=uy1uh4dpqf0C&dat=18770825&printsec=frontpage&hl=en|title=Daily Fort Worth Standard - Google News Archive Search|website=news.google.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83040340/1877-09-01/ed-1/seq-1/#date1=1877&index=5&date2=1877&searchType=advanced&language=&sequence=0&words=Hardin+John+Wesley&proxdistance=5&state=&rows=20&ortext=&proxtext=John+Wesley+hardin&phrasetext=&andtext=&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=1 |title=Hardin |date= September 1, 1877|publisher=The Iola Register }}</ref> Hardin claimed that he was captured while smoking his pipe and Duncan only found Hardin's pistol under his shirt after his arrest.<ref name="Hardin Autobiography" />{{rp|119}}

== Trial and imprisonment ==

Hardin was tried for Webb's killing, and on June 5, 1878, was sentenced to serve 25 years in [[Huntsville Prison]]. In 1879, Hardin and 50 other convicts were stopped within hours of successfully tunneling into the prison armory.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn86088181/1879-01-18/ed-1/seq-4/#date1=1877&index=10&date2=1892&searchType=advanced&language=&sequence=0&words=Hardin+John+Wesley&proxdistance=5&state=Texas&rows=20&ortext=&proxtext=John+Wesley+Hardin&phrasetext=&andtext=&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=1 |title=Article  |publisher=San Marcos Free Press |date= January 18, 1879|work= Library of Congress |page= 4| accessdate= December 1, 2013}}</ref> Hardin made several attempts to escape.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn86089443/1878-12-27/ed-1/seq-2/#date1=1877&index=0&date2=1892&searchType=advanced&language=&sequence=0&words=escape+Hardin&proxdistance=5&state=Texas&rows=20&ortext=&proxtext=Hardin+escape&phrasetext=&andtext=&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=1 |title=State News |publisher=Brenhan Weekly Banner |date= December 27, 1878 |work= Library of Congress  |page= 2 | accessdate=December 1, 2013}}</ref> During his prison term, on February 14, 1892, he was convicted of another manslaughter charge for the earlier shooting of J.B. Morgan and given a two-year sentence to be served concurrently with his unexpired 25-year sentence.<ref name="Hardin Autobiography" />{{rp|79}}<ref>Texas Convict Ledgers and Conduct Registries, 1849-1970;</ref>

Hardin eventually adapted to prison life. While there, he read theological books, becoming the superintendent of the prison Sunday School, and studied law. He was plagued by recurring poor health, especially when the wound he had received from Sublett became re-infected in 1883, causing him to be bedridden for almost two years. In 1892, Hardin was described as 5 feet 9 inches tall and 160 pounds, with a fair complexion, hazel eyes, dark hair, and wound scars on his right knee, left thigh, right side, hip, elbow, shoulder, and back. During Hardin's stay in prison, his first wife, Jane, died, on November 6, 1892.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn86089174/1892-11-21/ed-1/seq-2/;words=Hardin |title=News In Brief|date= November 21, 1892 |publisher =The Daily Herald News |work= Library of Congress|page= 2 }}</ref>

While in prison, he wrote an autobiography. He was well known for wildly exaggerating or completely making up stories about his life. He claimed credit for many murders that cannot be corroborated. Hardin wrote that he was first exposed to violence in 1861 when he saw a man named Turner Evans stabbed by John Ruff. Evans died of his injuries and Ruff was jailed. Hardin wrote, "... Readers you see what drink and passion will do. If you wish to be successful in life, be temperate and control your passions; if you don't, ruin and death is the result."<ref name="Hardin Autobiography"/>{{rp|10–11}}

== After prison ==

Hardin was released from prison on February 17, 1894, having served seventeen years of his twenty-five-year sentence.<ref name="NewYork"/> He was forty years old when he returned to Gonzales, Texas. Later that year, on March 16, Hardin was [[pardon]]ed, and, on July 21, he passed the state's [[bar examination]], obtaining his license to practice law.<ref name="Metz"/> According to a newspaper article in 1900, shortly after being released from prison, Hardin committed [[negligent homicide]] when he made a $5 bet that he could "at the first shot" knock a Mexican man off the soap box on which he was "sunning" himself, winning the bet and leaving the man dead from the fall and not the gunshot.<ref name="NewYork"/>

On January 9, 1895, Hardin married a 15-year-old girl named Callie Lewis. The marriage ended quickly, although it was never legally dissolved.<ref name="Metz" />{{rp|214–217}} Afterward, Hardin moved to [[El Paso, Texas]].

[[File:John Wesley Hardin Grave and Cage.jpg|thumb]]

== Death ==

[[File:John Wesley Hardin post mordem.jpg|right|thumb|Hardin's post mortem photo]]

An El Paso lawman, John Selman, Jr., arrested Hardin's acquaintance and part-time prostitute, the "widow" M'Rose (or Mroz), for "brandishing a gun in public". Hardin confronted Selman and the two men argued. Some accounts state that Hardin pistol-whipped the younger man. Selman's 56-year-old father, Constable [[John Selman|John Selman, Sr.]] (himself a notorious gunman and former outlaw), approached Hardin on the afternoon of August 19, 1895, and the two men exchanged heated words.<ref name="NewYork"/> That night, Hardin went to the Acme Saloon, where he began playing dice. Shortly before midnight, Selman Sr. entered the saloon, walked up to Hardin from behind, and shot him in the head, killing him instantly. As Hardin lay on the floor, Selman fired three more shots into him.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn95060914/1895-08-30/ed-1/seq-1/;words=Wesley+John+Hardin  |title=Article |date= August 30, 1895 |publisher=Graham Guardian |page= 1}}</ref> Selman Sr. was arrested for murder and stood trial. He claimed self-defense, stating that he witnessed Hardin attempting to draw his pistol upon seeing him enter the saloon, and a hung jury resulted in his being released on bond, pending retrial. However, before the retrial could be organized, Selman was killed in a shootout with [[US Marshal]] [[George Scarborough]] on April 6, 1896, during an argument following a card game.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85058130/1896-04-06/ed-1/seq-2/;words=Scarborough+George |title=Scarborough |date= April 6, 1896 |publisher=Salt Lake Herald |page= 2}}</ref>

Hardin was buried the following day<ref name="1995appeal"/> in Concordia Cemetery, in El Paso.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.concordiacemetery.org/products.html |title=John W Hardin 1853–1895  gravestone; |publisher=Concordia Heritage Association |accessdate= August 19, 2014}}</ref>

== Reburial controversy ==

[[File:Jw-hardin-gravestone.jpg|The grave of John Wesley Hardin|thumb|right]]
A century later, on August 27, 1995, there was a confrontation between two groups at the site of Hardin's grave. One group, representing several of Hardin's great-grandchildren, sought to relocate his body to Nixon, Texas, to be interred next to the grave of his first wife, Jane. The other group, consisting of locals from El Paso, sought to prevent the move. At the cemetery, the group representing Hardin's descendants presented a disinterment permit for the body, while the El Pasoans presented a court order prohibiting its removal. Both sides accused the other parties of seeking the tourist revenue generated by the location of the body. A subsequent lawsuit ruled in favor of keeping the body in El Paso.<ref name="1995appeal">{{cite web |url=https://caselaw.findlaw.com/tx-court-of-appeals/1216054.html  |title=Billings v. Concordia Heritage Association, Inc.|publisher=Find Law| accessdate= August 19, 2014}}</ref>

== Known contacts with the law ==

Hardin had numerous confirmed clashes with the law:

* January 9, 1871: Arrested by Constable E.T. Stakes and 12 citizens in [[Harrison County, Texas]] on a charge of four murders and one horse theft.<ref>Texas State Police arrest reports for 1870—1871;he is listed as "Hardin, J.R."</ref> (It is alleged that Hardin was an accomplice in the killing of ex-Texas State Policeman and Waco Texas Town Marshal Laban John Hoffman January 6, 1871. Hardin claimed not to have been involved in Hoffman's murder.<ref name="Hardin Autobiography" />{{rp|30}})
* January 22, 1871: Hardin killed [[Texas State Police]] officer Jim Smalley and escaped.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn84022278/1871-03-11/ed-1/seq-1/#date1=03/11/1871&index=0&date2=03/20/1871&searchType=advanced&language=&sequence=0&words=Smalley&proxdistance=5&state=Texas&rows=20&ortext=&proxtext=Smalley&phrasetext=&andtext=&dateFilterType=range&page=1|title=Dallas herald. (Dallas, Tex.) 1849-1873, March 11, 1871, Image 1|date=11 March 1871|publisher=|via=chroniclingamerica.loc.gov}}</ref> Up to November 13, 1872, the Grand Jury of [[Freestone County, Texas]] had not filed an indictment against Hardin for Smalley's killing.<ref name="ReferenceA">[http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=pv&GRid=11430987&PIpi=46876344 "Daily Democrat Statesman"]; August 30, 1877 article; [[Find-a-Grave]] online</ref>
* August 6, 1871: In Abilene, [[Dickinson County, Kansas]], Charles Couger was killed in the American House Hotel. Hardin, aka "Wesley Clemens", was found guilty by a coroner's jury of the killing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://api.ning.com/files/HXLvFMxAKuwK78-OlobUOkZ6eWSagJQ94TBijqoPWfyfZa6Q4Ohxm4QRFqoRXcIWrqceocyUhUBKqI7STkNejCwAV0L2IAEy/Image28.jpg|title=''Abilene Daily Chronicle'' August 10, 1871|publisher=}}</ref>
* October 6, 1871: [[Texas Special Police]]men Green Paramore is killed by Hardin and John Lackey is wounded in Gonzales, Texas.
* July 26, 1872: Texas State Policeman Sonny Speights was wounded in the shoulder by Hardin in [[Hemphill, Texas]]<ref name="Hardin Autobiography" />{{rp|65–67}}<ref name="ReferenceA"/>
* September 1872: Hardin surrendered to Sheriff Reagan, but escaped in October 1872.<ref>[http://www.tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/fha63 ''Article'']; Handbook of Texas</ref>
* November 19, 1872: Hardin mysteriously escaped from the sheriff of Gonzales County, Texas, despite a guard of six men. A reward of $100 was offered for his re-capture.<ref name="ReferenceA"/>
* May 1873: Hardin killed Dewitt County Texas ex-<nowiki/>{?}Deputy Sheriff Morgan and later killed Dewitt County Sheriff Jack Helms<ref name="Hardin Autobiography" />{{rp|79–82}}
* June 17, 1873: Hardin assisted in the escape of his brother-in-law, outlaw Joshua "Brown" Bowen, from the Gonzales County, Texas jail. Bowen had been charged with the December 17, 1872 killing of Thomas Holderman. After Bowen's execution in the summer of 1878, Hardin was implicated in Holderman's death as well.<ref>[http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn86089443/1879-06-13/ed-1/seq-1/;words=Wesley+John+Hardin ''Brenham Weekly Banner'']; June 13, 1879; p. 1 col. 3; [[Chronicling America]] online</ref>
* October 1873: Hardin was indicted in Hill County, Texas, for the 1870 death of Benjamin Bradley, but was never tried.<ref name="DMN2">[http://api.ning.com/files/watUoV6o8pvjdf*rrZseN*spcIP4QWSGijGoxdBUVBSBtNUmC1zu6bx1Zu487uPcVQAYDHRZzdxuwiJ51eXOSrizBla6sHBM/Image25.jpg ''Article''] Dallas Morning News; August 31, 1895; p.1</ref><ref name="DMN1"/>
* May 26, 1874: Hardin killed Brown County Deputy Sheriff Charles Webb in Comanche, Texas.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dlsEAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA369&dq=tried%20to%20Arrest%20John%20Wesley%20hardin&lr=#v=onepage&q=tried%20to%20Arrest%20John%20Wesley%20hardin&f=false|title=Cases Argued and Adjudged in the Court of Appeals of the State of Texas|first1=Texas Court of|last1=Appeals|first2=Alexander M.|last2=Jackson|date=1 January 1879|publisher=Gilbert Book Company|via=Google Books}}</ref>
* November 1876: Hardin (under the alias of "Swain") and Gus Kennedy were arrested in Mobile, Alabama and ordered to leave town.<ref>[http://mediasvc.ancestry.com/v2/image/namespaces/60623/media/0f856ee1-fbd3-4a17-9742-959eaddb6262.jpg?client=Boards "A Brace of Swindlers"] Article; ''Mobile Daily Register''; November 12, 1876; p. 1 Col. 2;</ref><ref name=Wright/>
* August 1877: Reported to have been under indictments in five Texas counties-[[Trinity County, Texas]]; [[Comanche County, Texas]] and [[Wilson County, Texas]] (the last was in July 1873 for killing of Sherriff Jack Helms) on three separate murder charges and in [[Navarro County, Texas]] and [[Smith County, Texas]] on two separate charges of assault with intent to murder.<ref name="ReferenceA"/>
* May 1, 1895: Hardin uses a pistol to get back money he had lost gambling at El Paso's Gem Saloon.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn86071158/1895-05-03/ed-1/seq-8/|title=Fort Worth gazette. (Fort Worth, Tex.) 1891-1898, May 03, 1895, MAILABLE EDITION., Image 8|date=3 May 1895|publisher=|pages=8|via=chroniclingamerica.loc.gov}}</ref> Hardin would later publish a defense of his action.<ref>[http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn86089174/1895-05-20/ed-1/seq-4/] Brownsville Texas ''The Daily Herald'' May 20, 1895 .p.4  Library of Congress</ref>
* July 1895: Fined $25 for gaming after using a pistol to get back money (a result of losing $100 at the Gem Saloon some weeks before).<ref>[http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn86089174/1895-07-09/ed-1/seq-4/;words=Wesley+John+Hardin ''The Daily Herald'']; July 9, 1895; p. 4; at [[Chronicling America]] online</ref> His gun was confiscated.<ref name="FamousFirearms">{{cite book | last = Herring| first = Hal| authorlink = | coauthors = | title =Famous Firearms of the Old West: From Wild Bill Hickok's Colt Revolvers to Geronimo's Winchester, Twelve Guns That Shaped Our History | publisher = TwoDot| year = 2008| location = | pages =224 | isbn = 0-7627-4508-8 }}</ref>

== Confirmed claims ==

* Prior to December 9, 1868, Hardin shot and mortally wounded "Maje"/Major Holshousen near Moscow, Polk County, Texas.
* January 5, 1870 – Hardin killed Benjamin Bradley and claimed to have brought about the "disappearance" of a "Judge Moore." in Hill County, Texas.
* January 6, 1871 – Hardin was alleged to be an accessory in killing of Waco Town Marshal Laban John Hoffman.
* January 22, 1871 – Hardin killed Texas State Policeman John Smalley.
* June 1, 1871 – Hardin killed three unknown Mexican vaqueros in Park City, Sedgwick County Kansas.
* July 20, 1871 – Hardin killed an unknown Mexican bandit in Sumner County, Kansas.
* August 6, 1871 – Hardin killed Charles Couger in Abilene, Kansas.
* October 6, 1871 – Hardin killed Texas Special Policeman Green Paramore and wounded John Lackey.
* June 19, 1872 – Hardin was wounded in a gunfight in Willis Texas.
* July 26, 1872 – Hardin wounded Texas State Policeman Sonny Speights in Hemphill, Texas.
* August 1872 – Hardin was indicted for murder in Trinity County, Texas.
* Dec 17, 1872 – Thomas Holderman is killed by Hardin's brother-in-law; Hardin was implicated in killing as well.
* May 15, 1873 – Jim Cox and Jake Christman were killed in the Sutton-Taylor feud; Hardin refused to confirm or deny he was involved in their deaths.
* May 17, 1873 – Hardin killed J.P. Morgan in Cuero, Texas and later killed Dewitt Sheriff [[Jack Helm]] in [[Albuquerque, Texas]].
* March 11, 1874 – William Sutton and Gabriel Slaughter were killed in the Sutton-Taylor feud; Hardin admitted to being involved in their deaths.
* May 26, 1874 – Hardin killed Deputy Sherriff Charles Webb in Comanche, Texas.
* March 1876 – Hardin wounded W.C. Overby in Florida.
* August 1877 – Hardin was wanted in three Texas counties for murder and in two Texas counties for assault with intent to murder.

== Unconfirmed claims ==

Hardin's autobiography is filled with statements which cannot be confirmed independently from his book:

* Hardin claimed that after killing Maje, he shot three [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] soldiers of the [[U.S. 4th Cavalry Regiment]] at a creek crossing at Logallis Prairie (now [[Nogalus Prairie, Texas|Nogalus Prairie]], Trinity County, Texas).<ref name="Hardin Autobiography" />{{rp|14}} None of the military records name Hardin as a suspect, nor do any facts agree with his claims.<ref>"Executive Documents Printed by order of the House of Representatives, 1868–1869"; Summary of Reports for the [[Fifth Military District]], August 1867–September 1868; reporting four soldiers killed and four wounded from the U.S. 6th Cavalry Regiment</ref> Circumstantial evidence is that a murder was committed here, but the names and numbers of victims are unknown.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.texasescapes.com/EastTexasTowns/Nogalus-Prairie-Texas.htm|title=Nogalus Prairie Texas, Nogales Prairie Texas, Nogallis Prairie Texas.|publisher=}}</ref>.<ref group=notes>See Chuck Parsons "A Lawless Breed: John Wesley Hardin, Texas Reconstruction, and Violence in the Wild West ...".p.25</ref>
* Hardin said he shot one of the two soldiers killed in 1869, in "Richland Bottom", the other having been shot by his cousin, Simpson "Simp" Dixson, a member of the [[Ku Klux Klan]] and a man who hated Union soldiers.<ref name="Hardin Autobiography" />{{rp|17}} <ref group=notes>Hardin claimed that Dixon's mother, sisters, and brother had been tortured and killed by Union soldiers during the Civil War. In fact, Dixon's mother had been divorced in 1851.  A brother was killed, but in 1868 during the Lee-Peacock feud.</ref> Records indicate that a Sgt. J.F. Leonard of Company B, 6th U.S. Cavalry, was wounded at Livingston, Texas, on May 7, 1869.<ref>"Executive Documents Printed by order of the House of Representatives, 1868–1869"; Summary of Reports for the [[Fifth Military District]], August 1867–September 1868, March 1868 supplement; a report against Lee's band.</ref> Simp "Dixson/Dickson" was killed by US soldiers In February 1870<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn84022278/1870-02-19/ed-1/seq-2/#date1=01%2F01%2F1870&index=12&date2=03%2F31%2F1870&searchType=advanced&language=&sequence=0&words=kill+killed+killing&proxdistance=5&state=Texas&rows=20&ortext=&proxtext=&phrasetext=killed&andtext=&dateFilterType=range&page=1] ''Dallas Herald'' February 19, 1870, Image 2 "Death of Simp Dickson" Library of Congress, accessed September 14, 2018</ref>
* In January 1870, Hardin claimed he killed a circus hand at Horn Hill, Texas. A contemporary newspaper account did report a fight in Union Hill, Texas, between circus "canvasmen" and "roughs" who tried to get in without paying, although the outcome did not conclude the way Hardin claimed it did.<ref>[http://fultonhistory.com/Process%20small/Newspapers/New%20York%20NY%20Clipper%201853%20-%201924/New%20York%20NY%20Clipper%201867-1870%20pdf/New%20York%20NY%20Clipper%201867-1870%20-%201192.pdf ''The Orton Brothers Circus'']; The New York Clipper; article; February 12, 1870; p.359, col. 4. "The Orton Brothers Circus had a "cleaning" match on Jan 21st at Union Hill, Texas. Some roughs tried to pass into the show without paying, but the canvas boys went for the crowd and "cleaned" them. After the concert at eight three roughs returned and commenced firing on the canvasmen. None of the circus boys were hurt, but one of the roughs was reported to have died the following day"</ref>
* A few days later, Hardin  killed a man in [[Kosse, Texas]];<ref name="Nash1989">{{cite book|author=Jay Robert Nash|title=Encyclopedia of Western Lawmen & Outlaws|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xNIdCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA144|date=3 January 1989|publisher=M. Evans|isbn=978-1-59077-530-1|page=144}}</ref> there are no contemporary newspapers to confirm this shooting.<ref group=notes>See Chuck Parsons "A Lawless Breed: John Wesley Hardin, Texas Reconstruction, and Violence in the Wild West ...".p.117</ref> Author Charles Adkins in his 1970 book "Texas, Guns & History" claimed the victim was named Alan Comstock; however he did not furnish any references to back up his claim.
* Hardin claimed that following his January 1871 escape from Stakes and Smalley, he killed a Mr. Smith, a Mr. Jones, and a Mr. Davis in [[Bell County, Texas]].<ref name="Hardin Autobiography" />{{rp|32}} No contemporary newspaper accounts from Bell County confirm these additional killings.
* Another claim was that he killed a man in Abilene, Kansas, in the summer of 1871. No contemporary newspaper accounts with evidence of such a killing exist-although a 1924 account does report a saloon shooting in some respects similar to Hardin's version.<ref group=notes>Although there are no contemporary newspaper reports of this shooting, this killing is mentioned in a 1924 account by Texas cattleman George N. Steen, who reported: ''While we were there one night, a man was drinking at a bar in a saloon, and somebody fired in from outside, the bullet striking him in the mouth and instantly killing him ... ''; from ''The Trail Drivers of Texas, Part One''; pub. 1924; Hunter, J. Marvin; p. 140.</ref>
* Hardin made the claim to have outdrawn "Wild Bill" Hickok. No contemporary newspaper accounts confirm this, but another report suggests that it was Hickok who made Hardin put up his guns.
* Hardin claimed that after killing Green Paramore in October 1871, he forced an African-American [[posse comitatus (common law)|posse]] to flee after killing three of them.<ref name="Hardin Autobiography" />{{rp|63}} There are no contemporary accounts to confirm this claim.
* Hardin claimed that on June 19, 1872, in [[Willis, Texas]], some men tried to arrest him for carrying a pistol, "... but they got the contents instead".<ref name="Hardin Autobiography"/>{{rp|63–65}} Hardin was wounded in a gunfight around this time, but records indicate the fight occurred with just one other man.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ci.willis.tx.us/DocumentCenter/View/222|title=''Summary'']; Texas Document Center; p. 4; retrieved |publisher=}}</ref>
* After being wounded by Sublett in August 1872, Hardin claimed that in September he either killed, or drove off, one or two members of the [[Texas State Police]] in Trinity, Texas.<ref name="Hardin Autobiography" />{{rp|72}} Hardin gave different versions of the event at different times. Although during his career he had killed two and wounded two of the Texas State policemen, these shootings did not occur in Trinity County. Likewise a check of the [ODMP] memorial website for 1872 shows only three Texas lawmen being killed in the line of duty-and not one of them even comes close to Hardins claim<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.odmp.org/|title=The Officer Down Memorial Page (ODMP)|publisher=}}</ref>
*September 1873 in Brooksville, Hernando County Florida a former slave named Allen May was shot and killed. A Savannah newspaper claimed the killer was John Wesley Hardin on a cattle Drive in Central Florida-but offered no proof Hardin was involved.<ref>[http://fivay.org/hernando1.html Website EARLY HERNANDO COUNTY HISTORY accessed September 21,2018]</ref>
* In May 1874, while in Gainesville, Florida, Hardin confessed to having knocked down a black man and shooting another during a disturbance outside the [[Alachua County]] jail. A black prisoner named "Eli", was lynched when the jail was burned down by a mob. Hardin claimed to have been part of the mob.<ref name="Hardin Autobiography"/>{{rp|110}}<ref group=notes>The Alachua county coroner afterward rendered the verdict that "Eli" had died after setting fire to the jail himself.</ref> No contemporary newspaper accounts support this, except one suggesting that the first Alachua County jail suffered a "demise".<ref>[http://www.alachuasheriff.org/pdfs/ACSO%20History%20Project%20Word%20version.pdf ''Article'']; alachuasheriff.org website; p.22</ref>
* Hardin claimed that on July 1, 1874, he drove off 17 [[Texas Ranger Division|Texas Rangers]] who had been trailing him, and killed one of them.<ref name="Hardin Autobiography" />{{rp|107}} This alleged shooting happened after a triple lynching of Hardin's cousin and two ranch hands. He also claimed to have driven off another group of men after killing one of them. There are no contemporary reports to confirm these stories. However, on June 1, 1874, a Texas Ranger's company did kill Hardin's cousins, Alexander Barekman and Alexander Anderson, in a gunfight and claimed to have wounded Hardin as well. Hardin wrote about his cousins' killings but does not confirm that he was wounded at all, and claimed to have heard about their deaths later.<ref name="Hardin Autobiography" />{{rp|102}}
* Later, Hardin and Mac Young were supposedly stopped near [[Bellville, Texas]] by a posse under Sheriff Charles Langhammer of [[Austin, Texas|Austin]] on suspicion of being horse thieves. Hardin pulled his guns on Langhammer but did not shoot him, fleeing instead; Young was arrested and fined $100 for having a concealed pistol.<ref name="Hardin Autobiography"/>{{rp|107–108}}
* Hardin claimed to have been involved in the killing of two [[Pinkerton National Detective Agency|Pinkerton agents]] on the Florida-Georgia border sometime between April and November 1876, after a gunfight with a "Pinkerton Gang" who had been tracking him from Jacksonville, Florida.<ref name="Hardin Autobiography" />{{rp|111}} This confrontation is pure fiction, as the Pinkerton Detective Agency never pursued Hardin. However, in March 1876 it was alleged Hardin, aka Swain, had wounded W.C. Overbey, who had tried to act as a mediator between Hardin and another person.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=dBzKUGQurMsC&dat=19861012&printsec=frontpage&hl=en  |title=The Law Catches Up with John Wesley Hardin |publisher=Gainesville Sun |date=October 12, 1986 |page=36 |author=B. Foster |quote=quoting the Gainesville Times of September 1, 1877}}</ref>
* Hardin claimed that in a saloon on election night in November 1876, he and a companion, [[Jacksonville, Florida|Jacksonville]] policeman Gus Kennedy, were involved in a gunfight with [[Mobile, Alabama|Mobile]] policemen in which one person was wounded and two killed. He further claims that he and Kennedy were arrested and later released.<ref name="Hardin Autobiography" />{{rp|111–112}} This appears to be another case of an exaggerated encounter. Hardin and Kennedy were simply arrested and driven out of town for cheating at cards.<ref>[http://mediasvc.ancestry.com/v2/image/namespaces/60623/media/0f856ee1-fbd3-4a17-9742-959eaddb6262.jpg?client=Boards ''Article'']; Mobile Daily Register; November 12, 1876; retrieved</ref> Again Hardin's version does not fit with contemporary records.<ref name=Wright>[http://boards.ancestry.com/localities.northam.usa.states.alabama.counties.mobile/3451.1/mb.ashx "A Gunfighters Southern Vacation"]; Wright, A.J.; National Association and Center for Outlaw History; vol VII, #3; Autumn 1982; quarterly; pp. 13–14; text shows difference between Hardin's version and contemporary accounts; accessed May 2016</ref>
* Hardin claimed to have met two fellow outlaws during his life: in 1870, he supposedly gambled with [[Bill Longley (gunfighter)|Bill Longley]].<ref name="Hardin Autobiography" />{{rp|25–27}} It is possible they could have met after both were sentenced for their crimes—Hardin receiving 25 years and Longley execution. Longley, who boasted of having killed as many men as Hardin, was outraged at the different degrees of sentencing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historynet.com/boastful-bill-longley-cold-blooded-texas-killer.htm|title=Boastful Bill Longley: Cold-blooded Texas Killer - HistoryNet|website=www.historynet.com}}</ref> After being sentenced in September 1878, Hardin supposedly met [[Johnny Ringo]], a fellow convict,<ref name="Hardin Autobiography" />{{rp|125}} in an Austin, Texas jail; in fact, Ringo had been acquitted and freed in May 1878<ref>See [http://johnnyringo.com/jrtexas.html Johnny Ringo History Page website] Note # 22. Accessed September 21, 2018]</ref>

== Legacy ==
{{further|John Wesley Hardin in popular culture}}
The memorable circumstances and sheer number of Hardin's life events, real or exaggerated, made him a legend of the Old West and an icon of American folklore. His autobiography was published posthumously in 1925 by [[Bandera, Texas|Bandera]] publisher, historian, and journalist [[J. Marvin Hunter]], founder of ''Frontier Times'' magazine and the [[Frontier Times Museum]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/fhu35|title=Wayne Gard, "John Marvin Hunter"| publisher=Handbook of Texas |website=tshaonline.com| accessdate=July 8, 2009}}</ref>

== Firearms and effects ==

Hardin's weapons of choice, and several of his personal effects, have been well documented and auctioned to private collectors. Court records show that John Wesley Hardin carried a [[Colt Model 1877|Colt "Lightning"]] revolver at the time of his death.<ref group=notes>The Colt's serial number was 84304: the gun was recorded in Colt factory ledgers as shipped on July 16, 1891, to Hartley & Graham, New York City. The Colt was accompanied by a tooled leather holster, marked with a barely visible stamp of an El Paso maker.</ref> He also carried an [[Elgin National Watch Company|Elgin watch]]<ref>serial number 4069110</ref> when he was shot and killed. The revolver and the watch had been presented to Hardin in appreciation for his legal efforts on behalf of [[Jim Miller (outlaw)|Jim Miller]] at Miller's trial for the killing of ex-sheriff George "Bud" Frazer. The Colt, with a [[.38 Long Colt|.38-caliber]], {{frac|2|1|2}}" barrel, is nickel-plated, with [[Bluing (steel)|blue]]d hammer, trigger, and screws. It features [[mother-of-pearl]] grips, and the back-strap is hand-engraved "J.B.M. TO J.W.H.". This gun and its holster were once sold at auction for $168,000. Another Colt revolver (known as a [[.41 Long Colt|.41-caliber]] "Thunderer"), which was owned by Hardin and used by him to rob the Gem Saloon, was sold at the same auction for $100,000.<ref name="FamousFirearms"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.truewestmagazine.com/stories/hardin_s_hardware/1006/|title=Hardin's Hardware|date=1 July 2006|publisher=}}</ref>

In 2002, an auction house in San Francisco, California, auctioned three lots of John Wesley Hardin's personal effects. One lot containing a deck of his playing cards, one of his business cards, and a contemporary newspaper account of his death, sold for $15,250. The bullet that killed Hardin sold for $80,000.<ref name = "auction1">Nolte, Carl.(2002). ''[http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2002/06/04/MN218566.DTL&type=printable Fastest draw at the auction house: Collectors snap up antique firearms, Old West memorabilia]''; San Francisco Chronicle; June 4, 2002</ref>

